Monotonically increasing id — monotonic, not sequential.

People reach for the monotonically-increasing-id function looking for a row number, and it is not one. Read the name literally and it tells you exactly what you get.

Monotonic means that within a single run, every id is strictly greater than the previous id generated in the same partition. So the numbers always go up. That part people get right.

But it is not sequential. The function packs the partition index into the upper bits and a per-partition counter into the lower bits. So across partition boundaries you get enormous jumps — you might go from two, straight to eight and a half billion. The numbers climb, but with giant gaps.

And it is not deterministic across runs. Re-execute the job and the same row can get a different id, because partition assignment can shift between runs.

So here is the decision. When you need dense, sequential, deterministic numbering, use row-number over a window — that is precisely what it is for, at the cost of a global shuffle. When you just need a cheap unique id and do not care about gaps, monotonically-increasing-id is fine. And when you need a stable key that survives across runs, neither works — generate a u-u-i-d, or hash your business-key columns instead.
